This 55-year-old gentleman presents to the office today because of right leg weakness. He does not really remember what happened but he states that approximately six months ago he was unable to stand on his right toe. Since that time he has had difficulty pushing off on his right toe and his toes have been tingling and numb. This has been an ongoing problem that has remained the same since the weakness began. He has had back pain for many years and it has not changed. He has had bilateral calves cramps for about a year and it stopped about two months ago. He has not had weakness in the left leg. He has not had pain around the right leg and the area of numbness and tingling. The problems with his right leg have not gotten worse or better. He has not had bowel or bladder incontinence, radicular pain. He was seen by a different physician in October a couple of months prior to his arrival at the office. We did a CT scan that shows degenerative changes, but nothing obviously abnormal. We did not do an MRI of his spine because of his ear implant. We were able to do an EMG and nerve conduction studies. He had an elevated CK prior to starting Lipitor. He is not taking Lipitor anymore. He thought that his CK was in the 500 to 600 prior to starting this medication. It apparently increased to about 800. It then came down to about 500 again when it was stopped. Recently he stopped taking Lipitor because his levels were up to the thousand's and then his CK apparently has returned to about the 500 to 600. No labs are available at this time. He just started Zetia. He has not had any weakness or pain after starting Zetia.
The patient did have a possible ingestion of a relatively small amount of liquid. It is likely to be a nontoxic ingestion as the patient is behaving as if she did not ingest any of the liquid.

She is unable to flex her knee at all. She is unable to straighten her knee out completely. She rates her pain today as a 10/10. She has been using ice and heat alternately. She is taking Tylenol with codeine and ibuprofen at home. She has noticed minimal improvement in her pain.

The patient is a 77-year-old white female who returns for followup. She was seen by Dr. XYZ for low back pain and lumbar scoliosis post laminectomy syndrome, lumbar spinal stenosis and symptomatic right L2 radiculopathy. She had a prior history of spinal stenosis and was treated with laminectomy. She developed low back pain and lumbar scoliosis post laminectomy syndrome, lumbar spinal stenosis and symptomatic right L2 radiculopathy. She was treated with injections into her L2-L3 L4 area in March 2005. She then returned to Dr. XYZ and he thought the symptoms were coming from her right hip. He did imaging on that hip on 08/04/04. X-rays today show marked degenerative changes and a progression from the x-rays taken back in August when she saw Dr. XYZ. He also did injections into her right hip on 04/07/2005 and last seen her on 04/15/2005. She is not sure if she wants to have a hip replacement at this time. She is having pain in her right hip today, especially with weight bearing. She has used a cane to get in and out of this hip. She has also made an appointment with an orthopedist in Newton. She is taking the generic Ultracet and takes it as many as four times a day. She is still in significant pain. She is taking Ultracet as many as four times a day.

Some days it would be fine, but other days it would hurt a little more. The recent injury made the pain worse. He is now feeling the pain more near the ulnar side of the wrist than the radial side.
